```zig
const std = @import("std");
const mem = std.mem;

pub fn transform(allocator: mem.Allocator, legacy: std.AutoHashMap(i5, []const u8)) mem.Allocator.Error!std.AutoHashMap(u8, i5) {
    var result = std.AutoHashMap(u8, i5).init(allocator);
    errdefer result.deinit();

    for (legacy.iterator()) |*entry| {
        const score = entry.key;
        const letters = entry.value;
        for (letters) |c| {
            const lower = std.ascii.toLower(c);
            try result.put(lower, score);
        }
    }

    return result;
}
```

message.reasoning:
We need to implement transform function: given legacy map from i5 (score) to []const u8 (string of uppercase letters). Need to produce new map from u8 (lowercase letter) to i5 (score). Use allocator to allocate new map. Return error!map.

Implementation: create new map: var result = std.AutoHashMap(u8, i5).init(allocator); defer? Actually we need to return map; caller will deinit. So we must not defer deinit inside function; we just init and fill, then return result. If any error occurs (e.g., put fails), we need to deinit result before returning error. So we can use errdefer result.deinit(); after filling, we return result.

Iterate over legacy entries: for (legacy.iterator()) |*entry| { const score = entry.key; const letters = entry.value; for (letters) |c| { const lower = @as(u8, std.ascii.toLower(c)); try result.put(lower, score); } }

Note: legacy map key type i5 (signed 5-bit?). Actually i5 is a signed integer with 5 bits? In Zig, i5 is a signed integer with width 5 bits. But we can treat as i5; we can just use it as is.

Edge: letters may be empty? Not needed.

Return result.

Make sure to include necessary imports.

Thus final code:

```zig
